This type of pasta is called ‚Äúriccia‚Äù - I get it at the Italian supermarket but you can use any kind of curly pasta like fusilli, maffaldine, etc.

Riccia with broccoli, spinach and burrata (serves 2)

1 head of broccoli, separate the florets and slice the stem (i use the entire thing!)
250g baby spinach
3 garlic cloves
4 tbsp pecorino or parmiggiano reggiano (i used parm today)
Chili flakes at your discretion
2 tbsp olive oil (best u can find)
200-300 gr of pasta (depending on how hungry you are)
1 mini burrata
Chopped pistachios
Salt and pepper

Start by boiling water and add 3 tsp of salt in a big pot. Once it boils, toss the broccoli, cook 5-7 min. Toss the spinach, cook 2-3 min. 

Drain the veg and in a bowl, use a fork to smash the vegetables, or if you have a hand blender you can coarsely puree it.

Finely Chop the garlic, heat up 2 tbsp olive oil in a non stick large pan. Once hot, add garlic, stir and add chili flakes. Once golden and aromatic, blend in the green puree thing, saut√© 1/2 minutes. Add the parmiggiano/pecorino), pepper and salt as u like.

Take the big pot, fill it again with water, add salt (1,5 tsp) and bring to boil. Cook the pasta until it‚Äôs 2 minutes to what it says in the box (you‚Äôll toss it in the pan later and cook some more, no worries). Save a cup of pasta water before draining the cooked pasta. Drain and toss it in the pan with the green cheesy stuff. Add 1/2 cup of pasta water, and while stirring keep cooking at high temp one minute, or until it gets creamy. If you think its a bit dry add more pasta water.

Plate, and very quickly cut a small burrata in half on a plate and scoop 1/2 of it on each plate, and finish w a tiny bit of oil and roughly chopped pistachio ü•¶ü•¶

Yesterday, for the first time in my 7 years in crypto, I fell for a scam.

I was enjoying a game some friends built and needed to top up my Redstone (L2 for games) wallet by bridging. Since Redstone's new i did not have it bookmarked, typed in the url and Google pointed me to a fake URL. I "bridged" and suddenly my Metamask was asking me to switch networks, to approve tokens, etc, and I understood what was going on.

Luckily I did not lose much money, I only have small amounts on my metamask and have lots of protecting software installed on my personal laptop.

Some members of the SEAL ORG helped me double check everything was okay as well.

Scams are getting more and more messed up, this time autofill from Google took me to a spoofed site.

So, some important things you need to know before interacting with crypto these days:

\- only have small amounts on hot wallets that highly interact with applications

\- download the revoke cash (revoke.cash) extension

\- double check URLs, bookmark everything you interact with safely

\- Never copy paste addresses from Etherscan, 0x addresses are not human readable and attackers can trick you into believing their address is yours, via generating "vanity addresses" use ENS as much as you possibly can.

Hey everyone please #LMCC! I made some new improvements on illustrating LIP-29, which aims to decentralize a User's algorithm by creating a free-market that's regulated by the users preferences. This works by establishing a "User Owned Algorithm" or "UOA" for short which is an NFT that has metadata containing the user's preferred algorithm. This UOA is read by apps in order to allow a user to have a say in what they see. This say or "preference" is expressed in two ways. One way is the User's profiles data from interactions that can be queried on Lens Protocol. This data is fed to the additional way that users curate what they see by choosing an "Agent." An agent determines what is included in an algorithm based on the users preferences coupled with the agents curation. In addition, the agent can hold "auctions" for any kind of ads that the user opts to include in their feed, or it can hold "auctions" on how much the user is willing to pay for similar paid content they want to include like news companies, sports, ext. The party interacting with the agent is called a "third party algorithm provider," whose role is to curate and bid at agents auctions. This interaction between agents and 3rd parties is meant to decentralize algorithm production and provide users with the cheapest and best content.

Now, when a user makes a post, that post can then be picked up by third party algorithm generator that then that post is either included or excluded by an agent. And, a user can always "force include" a profile though their social graph or some other mechanism by added it in a manual way to the UOA in any case of censorship attacks.

**Frames Kinda Suck (But They Don‚Äôt Have To)**

It‚Äôs cool to see Lens Frames being supported by more apps, but I fear that the hype around Frames has passed, and now we‚Äôre stuck in *the trough* with a user experience that kind of sucks.

**The Good**

Frames allow for some interesting use cases, effectively turning links into interactive mini-apps. This is especially interesting when combined with onchain activity, like using Open Actions, and passive games.

Frames are built on the Open Graph meta tags system. This is something you‚Äôve likely seen in many social apps ‚Äî it‚Äôs those website preview images that are automatically shown when a post or message contains a link. Frames extend that format to allow for actual interactions; essentially adding buttons to those link *embeds*.

There are many benefits to supporting Frames, like reducing the need to leave the feed, associating the interactions with a user‚Äôs social graph, and removing some friction of interacting directly with smart contracts.

**The Bad**

The problem is they‚Äôre really slow to use and generally have poor UX design. Frames break most best practices when it comes to web design. A Frame can show up to four buttons and a single input field. These buttons have no visual indication of their importance, danger, or relevance to the content. They‚Äôre generally visually identical. The input fields aren‚Äôt capable of providing basic niceties that you‚Äôve come to expect, like autocomplete, validation, and suggestions.

There‚Äôs no concept of navigation or history in Frames. You can‚Äôt simply go ‚Äúback‚Äù to see a previous Frame, or refresh the current Frame unless one (or more) of the 4 buttons is dedicated to navigation. This breaks typical expectations in using web interfaces and forces the Frame to use the limited real estate for adding basic functions.

One of the biggest issues with Open Graph tags, in general, is that most apps download the entire HTML document, then parse for the tags. This can be fairly slow and is terribly inefficient. For instance, just the HTML for a single YouTube video page is close to a 1MB download. Add a few of those to a feed and their impact becomes noticeable. For this reason, apps typically cache Open Graph tags to cut down the load times. Unfortunately, caching isn‚Äôt always possible with Frames because the images are often dynamic.

Another huge limitation for Frames is the necessity to present the UI as an image. This is terrible for accessibility, an inefficient use of resources, and reminds me of the worst aspects of the Flash days.

**The Solutions**

For starters, Frame UIs should have built-in navigation and history stack. It shouldn‚Äôt be up to the Frame to provide basic affordances like ‚Äúback‚Äù and ‚Äúrefresh‚Äù.

Frame buttons should allow for classification and denoting importance. *Dangerous* actions shouldn‚Äôt look the same as safe ones, and primary actions shouldn‚Äôt look the same as secondary or tertiary actions.

Apps that show Frames should use ‚Äústreaming‚Äù to download only the header of an HTML document, rather than downloading the entire thing and then parsing. This is a basic feature supported by the standard Javascript library for making web calls (`fetch`). In my limited testing it‚Äôs 5 - 10x faster.

Lastly, we need UI kits that standardize the way UIs are built in Frame images, and standards for accessibility so things like screen readers work with Frames. This would make it much easier for developers to present interfaces in a way that is familiar and expected.

Bonsai Token is going cross-chain, and I wanted to shed some light on how we‚Äôre thinking about it.

\* **how?** using the OFT standard from @lens/layerzero_labs

\* **where?** where onchain activity and strong communities are

\* **why?** extend the $BONSAI token network for the creator economy across chains

TLDR; we believe $BONSAI could be the first cross-chain token network to achieve the viral flywheel effect with monetization/rewards/incentives

**Bonsai OFT**

The OFT standard from LayerZero allows¬†tokens¬†to be transferred across chains without wrapping or third-party bridges. This means Bonsai Token will be supported on any EVM chain, and you can swap across them fast & cheap. We will host a bridge interface on the Bonsai website, and users of Stargate can bridge $BONSAI there too.

**Which chains are we looking to support?**

To decide which chains we‚Äôre focusing our efforts on - beyond @lens/zksync & Lens Network - we‚Äôre looking at where there‚Äôs trading volume, relevant onchain activity, and strong communities.

On the Lens Network, we anticipate that $BONSAI will remain the preferred currency for creators, enabling them to earn through various crypto social avenues. Whether it‚Äôs via collectible content, premium feeds, or innovative SocialFi open actions / frames - $BONSAI is set to be at the forefront of the creator economy.

As the zkSync Elastic Chain grows and more users are brought onchain - I expect the

@lens/lens social graph and $BONSAI token network to grow with it.

If we take a look at @lens/base - the majority of trading activity for Uniswap is happening there. Just this week, they shared a chart of the weekly Univ2 pairs. Base has 4.5x the pools that Ethereum has, and 170x the pools that Polygon has.

Base also boasts some of the strongest memecoin communities, including BasedBrett and $HIGHER. I‚Äôd personally love to find out what a Bonsai x Higher collab would look like, in terms of creative output.

**Why is Bonsai going cross-chain?**

On Lens, creators have been using $BONSAI to monetize their content and creative output. Users, curators and Orb Clubs are also able to earn their cut on referral fees. We could just migrate to zkSync / Lens Network and stop there. But as we see it, $BONSAI is already the de-facto culture currency in our ecosystem - and it would be more interesting for us to tap other onchain communities where they already are. And that‚Äôs currently on Base.

With apps like Boost and Layer3 - we‚Äôre able to use token incentives to help push mints to go viral onchain. Currently, creators like @lens/levy and those part of the BluePrint cohort are using $BONSAI to drive their mints on platforms like Pods & Zora.

If $BONSAI was also on Base, the collectors who redeemed those rewards could immediately spend them on other creators in the ecosystem. The flywheel effect we‚Äôre looking to achieve here is 1) earn tokens 2) spend them on creators 3) drive economic activity 4) earn tokens. Bonsai Token could be the first cross-chain token network to achieve this flywheel effect at scale across the onchain creator economy.

I think $DEGEN dropped the ball on being the culture currency for Base. They were too focused on the L3, rather than expanding on what was already working for them - tipping content on Farcaster. Tipping for the sake of tipping is not really interesting anymore.

I like the Club Treasury feature from @lens/orb to collectively earn & re-distribute tokens. It‚Äôs one step away from a DAO, and empowering them with a cross-chain culture currency like $BONSAI would enable them to participate in any onchain economy.

All this to say - I‚Äôm excited for this cross-chain future that‚Äôs coming for Bonsai. It won‚Äôt come without its hurdles, but it will be totally worth it in the long term.

There's a line in the timeless musical "Sweeney Todd" where the title character says, "At Last, My Right Arm is Complete." - While this is a slightly less bloody declaration, that's how I feel about visual AI.

By 1st grade, I played the violin, was an orator and writer, had read countless books, and was discovering a passion for theatre (still didn't know I could sing until 7th grade (a story for another time).


But I couldn't draw.


I remember walking up to the teacher's desk and giving myself an F. I was so frustrated that I could be so good at so many things but couldn't create art. But my imagination! I was devastated.

Flash forward to today- when I create a text prompt that's 20 years of art history, reference, and understanding of language. This new multi-hyphenated people have struggled and survived hardship and cruelty, erasure, and degradation. Yet still they rise. Society has taught us to shame this moment, but from this darkness there is empowerment, catharsis, and closure. When people ask me where I'm from I can always hold my head knowing that I am the descendant of Kings and Queens who survived one of the cruelest moments in history. ORIGINST√òRY was supposed to be a dance music project.

The pandemic hit hard for everyone and in the middle of it while trying to figure out the next move I found myself in the midst of depression and self-doubt. I quit music and didn't see a road back. But slowly, slowly around the middle of 2022 I started to find joy in creating again. I just let it flow, tried not to judge the process, and be open.  The rapid ascent of creative AI also gave me another tool, something I'd hoped for since childhood, but had given up on - the ability to create artistic scenes composed of the images and ideas in my mind.


Flash forward to today and the ORIGINST√òRY project has become rock and funk focused, filled with homages to the sounds that blasted from my childhood bedroom. It's not what I was expecting, but it couldn't be more appropriate. It was made for speakers, made for headphones, and definitely made for live.


This is a completely new adventure for me filled with all of the excitement and nerves of sharing yourself with the world for the first time. My hope in releasing this project into the Web3 world is that it might allow me to achieve dreams that I couldn't before.  I've seen so many wins for others in this space, I can't help but manifest some of that for myself and for the future. And I'm excited to see who joins along for the ride.
